## Just a precision though

A lambda is not a special interface, class or anything else you could declare by yourself. `Lambda` is just the name given to the `() -&gt; {}` special syntax, which allows better readability when passing single-method interfaces as parameter. It was designed to replace this :

    method(new Callback() {
        @Override
        public void call() {
            // Classic interface implementation, lot of useless boilerplate code.
            // method() is done, do whatever you want here.
        }
    });

So in the example above, `Callback` is **not** a lambda, it&#39;s just a regular interface ; `lambda` is the name of the shortcut syntax you can use to implement it.

